<subSubSection id="924212E65EACC800A73A84F65A146AB4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph id="2BF796F00F77EDB9993640B219E2629C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8D5F57716CC0D7D52321747520F037DF" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Compared to other 
<taxonomicName id="5ECAD00B20E07A869D638CA9A7EC2987" authorityName="Braschnikov" authorityYear="1897" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Ophiomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ophiomyia" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C0774531999AB7F4173FEE5C15E1BBA1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ophiomyia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with a fasciculus, 
<taxonomicName id="7C1C7ECE1447A7678D7C01C90EB985DB" family="Agromyzidae" genus="O." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="O. sexta" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="sexta">
<emphasis id="B6E58698E8241F0F040FCD3141BCB56B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">O. sexta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a relatively short genal process, three ori and quite closely spaced crossveins. Internally, the incredibly large distiphallus is characteristic, being brain-shaped in ventral view and dorsoventrally compressed.
</paragraph>
